<h2 id="three-kinds-of-alignment-work">Three kinds of alignment work</h2>

<p>But the alignment tax isnŌĆÖt just one thing. Here are some different ways I saw it showing up:</p>

<h3 id="semantic-alignment">Semantic Alignment</h3>

<p>Semantic alignment is when you and the model are using the same words but not meaning the same thing.</p>

<p>In my session, the clearest example was visual. I said ŌĆ£sparklesŌĆØ and meant blurry glowing halos, almost star-like. The model implemented tiny 1ŌĆō2px dots. Technically sparkles. Not remotely what I meant. We spent multiple rounds getting to the same picture with the same word.</p>

<p>ThatŌĆÖs not the model being irrational. ItŌĆÖs a reminder that language is doing more work than we think.</p>

<h3 id="structural-alignment">Structural Alignment</h3>

<p>Structural alignment is when you and the model are working from different maps of the territory.</p>

<p>At one point I asked it to find files in documents/ai blogpost. The model didnŌĆÖt have access to that directory. That wasnŌĆÖt obvious to either of us until it tried. The problem wasnŌĆÖt wording. It was environment.</p>

<h3 id="state-alignment">State Alignment</h3>

<p>State alignment is the ongoing work of keeping the model current as reality changes.</p>

<p>Placeholder filenames became real filenames. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes.db</code> became <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tapes.sqlite</code>. A new directory appeared, a file moved, a new project meant shifts in structure. Every time the ground truth shifted, there was work to sync the modelŌĆÖs working assumptions with what was actually true.</p>

